<subSubSection lastPageId="119" lastPageNumber="120" pageId="118" pageNumber="119" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="118.[151,1437,1397,2036]" lastBlockId="119.[151,1437,151,429]" lastPageId="119" lastPageNumber="120" pageId="118" pageNumber="119">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,308,1973,1999]" pageId="118" pageNumber="119">Remarks</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[324,600,1973,1999]" italics="true" pageId="118" pageNumber="119">
Petroliosthes 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Stimpson" authorityYear="1858" box="[479,600,1973,1999]" class="Malacostraca" family="Porcellanidae" genus="Petrolisthes" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="118" pageNumber="119" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tridentatus">tridentatus</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
was originally described from the E Lesser Antilles (
<collectingCountry box="[1213,1321,1973,1999]" name="Barbados" pageId="118" pageNumber="119">Barbados</collectingCountry>
and 
<collectingCountry name="Virgin Islands" pageId="118" pageNumber="119">Saint Thomas</collectingCountry>
) and is currently considered as a transisthmian species, although as 
<bibRefCitation author="Gore, R. H." box="[992,1129,2009,2035]" pageId="118" pageNumber="119" pagination="1 - 34" refId="ref72204" refString="Gore, R. H. (1982) Porcellanid crabs from the coasts of Mexico and Central America (Crustacea: Decapoda: Anomura). Smithsonian Contributions to Zoology, 363, 1 - 34. https: // doi. org / 10.5479 / si. 00810282.363" type="journal article" year="1982">Gore (1982)</bibRefCitation>
noted, “it is by far the more abundant in the Pacific, according to available collecting records”. It can be distinguished from the closely related species, especially 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Benedict" authorityYear="1901" box="[366,509,187,213]" class="Malacostraca" family="Porcellanidae" genus="Petrolisthes" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="119" pageNumber="120" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="quadratus">
<emphasis box="[366,509,187,213]" italics="true" pageId="119" pageNumber="120">P. quadratus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, by the anteriorly protruding, rounded lateral lobes. The species seems to be quite variable in the colour pattern. 
<bibRefCitation author="Stimpson, W." box="[489,677,222,249]" pageId="119" pageNumber="120" pagination="49 - 93" refId="ref76764" refString="Stimpson, W. (1859) Notes on North American Crustacea, No 1. Annals of the Lyceum of Natural History of New York, 7, 49 - 93. https: // doi. org / 10.1111 / j. 1749 - 6632.1862. tb 00142. x" type="journal article" year="1859">Stimpson (1859)</bibRefCitation>
noted that in the 
<typeStatus box="[873,921,223,249]" pageId="119" pageNumber="120">type</typeStatus>
specimens, the carapace was spotted with red and streaked down the middle with whitish, the P1 were dark reddish and the P2–P4 were banded. The carapace and P1 of the specimens from 
<collectingCountry box="[446,587,295,321]" name="Sint Martin" pageId="119" pageNumber="120">Saint Martin</collectingCountry>
and 
<collectingCountry box="[642,751,295,321]" name="Honduras" pageId="119" pageNumber="120">Honduras</collectingCountry>
(Utila) range from dark greenish brown with very few white spots (
<figureCitation box="[223,323,331,357]" captionStart="FIGURE 74" captionStartId="119.[151,250,1856,1880]" captionTargetBox="[213,1374,453,1833]" captionTargetId="figure-171@119.[213,1374,453,1833]" captionTargetPageId="119" captionText="FIGURE 74. Petrolisthes tridentatus Stimpson, 1859: A, B, extra-limital specimen, male (cl cw indet.) from Saint Martin (FLMNH UF 32075), dorsal (A) and ventral (B) views [photographs by AA]; C, extra-limital specimen, male from Saint Martin (FLMNH UF 31932), dorsal view [photograph courtesy of Gustav Paulay / François Michonneau]; D, extra-limital specimen, ovigerous female (cl cw indet.) from Utila, Honduras (not deposited), dorsal view; E, extra-limital specimen, male (cl cw indet.) from the same locality (not deposited), dorsal view [photographs by AA]." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5532396" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5532396/files/figure.png" pageId="119" pageNumber="120">Fig. 74C</figureCitation>
) or a mixture of brown and pale brown with more numerous white spots (
